schools, the Greek language and politics, etc. Besides, it offers new knowledge on the appreciation and reception of Cicero and his texts by the Greek world from Late Antiquity to Byzantium and Modern Greece, based on material deriving from a variety of sources (papyri, manuscripts, compendia or encyclopaedias, imitations, translations, early editions, etc.), an aspect of the relationships between Cicero and Greece still understudied. Thus, the volume offers an image as illustrative as possible of various aspects of the presence of the Greek world in Cicero's works and of Cicero's presence in Greece from his own times to the present day.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aAntike. 4aAntikenrezeption. 4aCicero. 4aGriechenland.  aCicero.  aGreece.  aantiquity.  areception.1 aDeligiannis, Ioannis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeligiannis, Ioannis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEvangelou, Gabriel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLu, Ximing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaffei, Fernanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliva, Matilde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOttobrini, Tiziano F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPappas, Vasileios, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTsouni, Georgia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook p